WEBVTT

00:05.396 --> 00:06.813
CATHERINE RAWSON:
You do know what people say
about her, don't you?

00:06.896 --> 00:08.229
She's a bit like a man.

00:08.313 --> 00:09.521
Don't be absurd.

00:11.396 --> 00:12.937
MAN: I understand
you're leasing out your coal.

00:13.021 --> 00:16.563
ANNE LISTER:
Per acre, 226 pounds,
17 shillings, and six pence.

00:16.730 --> 00:19.646
If I don't get my price,
I shall sink my own pits.

00:19.730 --> 00:21.146
CHRISTOPHER RAWSON:
I think she's bluffing.

00:21.229 --> 00:24.855
We should just bide our time
and see what happens.

00:25.605 --> 00:27.605
WOMAN: What she really needs
is a good friend.

00:27.688 --> 00:29.313
And perhaps, she's found one.

00:29.521 --> 00:32.187
I think you're a little bit
in love with me.

00:32.605 --> 00:34.937
ANN WALKER: I do have
tender feelings for you.

00:35.146 --> 00:37.479
I'm going on this excursion
with my cousin, Catherine.

00:37.688 --> 00:38.896
I wish you could come with us.

00:39.104 --> 00:40.479
LISTER:
I've been invited to a wedding.

00:40.563 --> 00:42.605
-I don't want to go.
-ANN: Why don't you want to go?

00:42.979 --> 00:44.313
LISTER: (SIGHS)
It's complicated.

00:44.396 --> 00:47.021
If you went,
the thing that seems complicated

00:47.104 --> 00:48.688
might sort itself out.

00:49.104 --> 00:50.563
We're going
to the Lake District.

00:54.896 --> 00:56.021
[TV static drones]

00:56.104 --> 00:58.146
[bright tone]

00:59.104 --> 01:02.021
[andante music]

01:02.104 --> 01:09.187
♪ ♪

01:24.646 --> 01:25.855
[laughter]

01:25.937 --> 01:28.062
[knocking on door]

01:28.146 --> 01:30.896
- Ma'am, Mrs. Stansfield Rawson

01:30.979 --> 01:32.563
and Miss Delia Rawson.

01:32.646 --> 01:35.229
- Oh, of course.
Show them in.

01:35.313 --> 01:37.438
- Oh, Miss Lister.

01:37.521 --> 01:39.521
- Mrs. Rawson.

01:39.605 --> 01:41.479
Miss Rawson.
- Do come in.

01:42.979 --> 01:44.813
How nice to see you.

01:44.937 --> 01:47.021
- How are you, my dear?

01:50.062 --> 01:51.479
- Miss Walker
is very well indeed,

01:51.563 --> 01:54.146
better than she's been
in a long time.

01:54.229 --> 01:56.021
And how are you?

01:56.104 --> 01:59.187
- I'm--I'm very well,
thank you.

01:59.271 --> 02:02.438
- Good.
Sit down.

02:02.521 --> 02:05.062
- Well, as you have company,

02:05.146 --> 02:07.062
perhaps we ought to come back
another time.

02:07.146 --> 02:09.479
- Oh, if you like.

02:17.521 --> 02:20.187
- You do look very well,
my dear.

02:20.271 --> 02:22.104
Your trip to the Lake District
with Catherine

02:22.187 --> 02:24.646
has obviously done you
a power of good.

02:24.730 --> 02:27.313
She's talked about nothing else
since she got home.

02:27.396 --> 02:28.646
- Your resemblance
to your sister

02:28.730 --> 02:30.813
is remarkable, Miss Rawson,

02:30.896 --> 02:32.438
except the lips,

02:32.521 --> 02:35.438
I think, are fuller.

02:38.146 --> 02:42.313
- How surprised we all were,
however, Miss Lister,

02:42.396 --> 02:45.896
when Catherine told us
that you had turned up

02:45.979 --> 02:48.062
so unexpectedly.

02:48.146 --> 02:50.771
- Oh, really?
But I adore the Lake District.

02:50.855 --> 02:52.563
Wild horses
wouldn't keep me away.

02:52.646 --> 02:54.187
Any excuse.

02:54.271 --> 02:56.979
And anyway, I had nothing else
to do that afternoon.

02:57.062 --> 02:58.396
[laughs]

03:01.563 --> 03:04.479
[jaunty music]

03:04.563 --> 03:11.646
♪ ♪

03:33.146 --> 03:34.855
- You definitely think
it's the right thing to do?

03:34.937 --> 03:36.937
- Yes.

03:37.021 --> 03:38.187
- She might laugh.

03:38.271 --> 03:40.771
- She'd be daft to laugh,
situation she's in.

03:42.313 --> 03:43.646
- I worry about us
not being able

03:43.730 --> 03:45.021
to speak the same language.

03:45.104 --> 03:46.479
- Oh, come.

03:46.563 --> 03:50.313
What you've got to be certain
about is, is it what you want?

03:50.396 --> 03:52.396
- First time I saw her.

03:52.479 --> 03:54.229
When she stepped out
of that high flyer

03:54.313 --> 03:56.771
and then spewed up,
I knew.

03:56.855 --> 03:59.021
- Well, then, it's worth
risking a refusal then,

03:59.104 --> 04:00.479
isn't it,
if you feel like that?

04:00.563 --> 04:02.479
- You'll be me best man,
won't you?

04:04.979 --> 04:05.896
Morning.

04:05.979 --> 04:08.771
- Hello, John.

04:08.855 --> 04:10.146
What's up?

04:11.605 --> 04:13.438
- We need your help.
Well, he does.

04:13.521 --> 04:15.187
- All right.

04:15.271 --> 04:16.479
- Well...

04:18.479 --> 04:19.354
I was--

04:19.438 --> 04:21.187
- He was wondering
about asking Eugénie

04:21.271 --> 04:22.855
how she might feel
about marrying me.

04:22.937 --> 04:24.271
- What?
- Him, him.

04:24.354 --> 04:25.229
Not me.
Him.

04:25.313 --> 04:27.146
- John Booth,
you dark horse!

04:27.229 --> 04:29.937
- Yes, only, obviously,
I'd need your help,

04:30.021 --> 04:32.021
Mrs. Cordingley,
to ask her.

04:32.104 --> 04:32.979
- So hang on.

04:33.062 --> 04:36.021
You want me to propose
by proxy for you?

04:36.104 --> 04:37.771
- Yes.
What do you think?

04:37.855 --> 04:39.979
- And to pass the baby off
as yours?

04:40.062 --> 04:42.605
- Yes, obviously.
That's the point.

04:42.688 --> 04:44.062
Eh, but if you could tell her
as well

04:44.146 --> 04:47.855
that I think
she's very beautiful

04:47.937 --> 04:50.688
and I'd be very honored

04:50.771 --> 04:54.937
and I'd do everything I could
to make her very happy.

04:55.021 --> 04:57.521
- Oh, isn't he lovely?

04:57.605 --> 04:58.771
If she won't have you, John,
I will.

04:58.855 --> 05:00.855
- You do know,
if she works it out,

05:00.937 --> 05:02.771
she'll sack you, and your feet
won't touch the ground.

05:02.855 --> 05:05.396
- Babies come early
all the time.

05:05.479 --> 05:08.438
[quiet music]

05:08.521 --> 05:13.229
♪ ♪

05:13.313 --> 05:14.979
- [knocking]

05:15.062 --> 05:16.605
- Eh...

05:16.688 --> 05:19.563
[speaking halting French]

05:28.021 --> 05:30.521
♪ ♪

05:30.605 --> 05:32.688
- Oui.

05:32.771 --> 05:33.979
- Really?

05:34.062 --> 05:36.979
[warm music]

05:37.062 --> 05:44.104
♪ ♪

05:50.229 --> 05:52.771
- If we do go to Switzerland
and Rome--

05:52.855 --> 05:53.688
- If?

05:53.771 --> 05:55.896
- [laughs]
Sorry. When.

05:55.979 --> 05:58.563
When we go to Switzerland
and then Rome,

05:58.646 --> 06:02.313
um, I can't go
until after February.

06:02.396 --> 06:04.521
I've got people,

06:04.605 --> 06:06.062
friends, coming to stay,

06:06.146 --> 06:07.896
and I can't really
put them off.

06:07.979 --> 06:09.104
I mean, I can,

06:09.187 --> 06:10.855
but it would just be easier
if I didn't.

06:10.937 --> 06:12.521
- of course.

06:12.605 --> 06:15.146
- But then once they've gone...
- Of course.

06:15.229 --> 06:17.688
- I mean, in many ways,
I'd like to put them off.

06:17.771 --> 06:20.646
I'd prefer it, but--
- If the thing's been arranged,

06:20.730 --> 06:23.146
you must stick with it.
- Mm.

06:23.229 --> 06:25.021
[wondrous music]

06:25.104 --> 06:26.813
[gasps]

06:26.896 --> 06:33.937
♪ ♪

06:41.521 --> 06:43.229
- Sit down.

06:43.313 --> 06:44.896
- [laughs]

06:44.979 --> 06:51.813
♪ ♪

06:57.229 --> 06:58.771
I was so happy

06:58.855 --> 07:01.396
when you turned up
in Eskdale.

07:01.479 --> 07:03.605
[laughs]

07:03.688 --> 07:05.813
I'd been, um...

07:05.896 --> 07:07.313
I'd been feeling rather low,

07:07.396 --> 07:10.062
and I-I knew
that if there was

07:10.146 --> 07:12.646
one face in the world
I'd be delighted to see,

07:12.730 --> 07:14.438
it was yours,

07:14.521 --> 07:15.563
and then there you were!

07:15.646 --> 07:17.605
[both laugh]

07:17.688 --> 07:20.521
- Mm.
- You know, um...

07:20.605 --> 07:23.937
before I went up there,

07:24.021 --> 07:25.104
that day,

07:25.187 --> 07:27.021
we were in my sitting room,

07:27.104 --> 07:29.771
and you said...

07:29.855 --> 07:32.605
Um...

07:32.688 --> 07:35.896
You implied that you...

07:35.979 --> 07:38.146
wanted to...

07:38.229 --> 07:40.605
♪ ♪

07:40.688 --> 07:42.563
Kiss me.

07:44.313 --> 07:46.521
And--and then
you were embarrassed,

07:46.605 --> 07:50.563
but, well,
you shouldn't have been.

07:50.646 --> 07:52.313
♪ ♪

07:52.396 --> 07:55.813
Because it doesn't frighten me.

07:55.896 --> 07:58.813
[tender music]

07:58.896 --> 08:01.979
♪ ♪

08:02.062 --> 08:03.813
- Really?

08:03.896 --> 08:10.937
♪ ♪

09:29.354 --> 09:30.354
- Married?

09:30.438 --> 09:31.813
- Yes, ma'am.

09:31.896 --> 09:36.021
So we wondered
if--if you--you c-could tell--

09:36.104 --> 09:37.646
ask Miss Lister.

09:37.730 --> 09:40.104
- Eugénie is
Anne's lady's maid,

09:40.187 --> 09:41.855
and you're outdoor staff, John,

09:41.937 --> 09:43.521
so strictly speaking,
that's her juris--

09:43.605 --> 09:46.229
- Yes, I know that, but...

09:46.313 --> 09:48.563
She won't like it, will she?
So--

09:48.646 --> 09:50.813
- So you want me
to be the messenger

09:50.896 --> 09:52.271
that gets shot?

09:54.646 --> 09:56.229
[sighs]
It's sudden.

09:56.313 --> 10:02.187
- Yes, but sometimes,
that's how it is.

10:02.271 --> 10:04.479
- I didn't know
you spoke any French, John.

10:06.062 --> 10:07.855
- Oui.

10:07.937 --> 10:10.896
[jaunty music]

10:10.979 --> 10:18.021
♪ ♪

10:20.146 --> 10:21.396
- I can't remember
when I've spent

10:21.479 --> 10:23.187
so pleasant a day.

10:24.479 --> 10:27.146
- I wonder if tomorrow,

10:27.229 --> 10:28.771
you might pay a call,

10:28.855 --> 10:31.104
a sort of formal call

10:31.187 --> 10:33.771
on my aunt.

10:33.855 --> 10:35.730
- Of course, if you like.

10:35.813 --> 10:38.771
[gentle music]

10:38.855 --> 10:40.438
Thank you, James.

10:40.521 --> 10:46.688
Um, and then,
tomorrow evening...

10:46.771 --> 10:49.229
would you like to
come for dinner,

10:49.313 --> 10:52.855
and then...

10:52.937 --> 10:54.979
stay all night?

10:55.062 --> 10:57.021
♪ ♪

10:57.104 --> 10:59.021
- [laughs]

10:59.104 --> 11:03.563
♪ ♪

11:03.646 --> 11:04.937
Are you sure?

11:05.021 --> 11:12.062
♪ ♪

11:13.896 --> 11:16.813
[upbeat music]

11:16.896 --> 11:23.937
♪ ♪

11:36.771 --> 11:37.896
- Where have you been?

11:37.979 --> 11:39.771
I was on the cusp of
sending the servants out

11:39.855 --> 11:40.855
looking for you.

11:40.937 --> 11:43.187
It's past 10:00.
It's pitch dark!

11:43.271 --> 11:44.229
You've been out all day.

11:44.313 --> 11:45.521
You didn't come back
for dinner.

11:45.605 --> 11:47.563
No one knew where you were!

11:47.646 --> 11:49.313
I had to send
for Dr. Kenny.

11:49.396 --> 11:51.354
- Why?
- For Aunt Anne!

11:51.438 --> 11:53.104
She's had spasms
in her stomach,

11:53.187 --> 11:54.229
not helped by the fact

11:54.313 --> 11:55.813
that she's been
in a host of miseries

11:55.896 --> 11:57.187
wondering where you were,

11:57.271 --> 11:59.021
imagining you'd had
your throat slit

11:59.104 --> 12:00.979
by a madman in the dark!

12:01.062 --> 12:02.937
Lock up!

12:04.937 --> 12:06.646
- Are you all right?
What happened?

12:06.730 --> 12:08.813
- Stomach cramps.

12:08.896 --> 12:10.813
- [sighs]
I was only over at Lightcliffe.

12:10.937 --> 12:12.605
- Yes.
We didn't know that, did we?

12:12.688 --> 12:14.563
- Thank you, Marian.
- You're impossible.

12:14.646 --> 12:16.062
- Yes.
- You're ridiculous.

12:16.146 --> 12:17.730
You're so selfish!
- Quite possibly.

12:17.813 --> 12:19.062
Now, I need to talk
to Aunt Anne.

12:19.146 --> 12:20.229
- Will you, in future,

12:20.313 --> 12:22.021
think about others
whilst you're living here?

12:22.104 --> 12:24.396
- Whilst--

12:24.479 --> 12:25.937
Yes, certainly.
Thank you.

12:26.021 --> 12:27.354
- Oh!
Oh!

12:27.438 --> 12:28.896
[irritated grunt]

12:28.979 --> 12:30.479
Right, good night.

12:30.563 --> 12:31.771
- She worries about you.

12:31.855 --> 12:34.187
- She needn't.
- But we all do.

12:34.271 --> 12:36.563
- As long as you're all right.
That's all that matters to me.

12:36.646 --> 12:38.937
- But where were you?

12:39.021 --> 12:43.021
- [sighs]
It's been a rather unusual day,

12:43.104 --> 12:44.688
and a happy one.

12:44.771 --> 12:47.438
I was with Miss Walker.

12:47.521 --> 12:49.646
We've become friends.

12:49.730 --> 12:52.521
She confides in me.
[sighs]

12:52.605 --> 12:56.438
We talk about
all sorts of things.

12:56.521 --> 13:00.396
I think she's become
really rather fond of me.

13:00.479 --> 13:02.229
I had begun to wonder--

13:02.313 --> 13:05.354
not that anything's
been said yet...

13:08.313 --> 13:14.979
If she might make
a companion of me,

13:15.062 --> 13:16.771
for life.

13:16.855 --> 13:21.271
- And does she seem
disinclined to marry?

13:21.354 --> 13:23.563
- She's 29.

13:23.646 --> 13:25.605
- She's 12 years
younger than you.

13:25.688 --> 13:29.937
Can't imagine
she's your intellectual equal.

13:30.021 --> 13:31.979
- Would that matter,

13:32.062 --> 13:34.688
if our tastes
were the same

13:34.771 --> 13:37.563
and we were fond
of one another?

13:41.521 --> 13:44.187
Is she vulgar?

13:44.271 --> 13:46.021
- No.
I thought the aunt was a bit,

13:46.104 --> 13:47.104
but not her.

13:47.187 --> 13:48.688
But where you would live?

13:48.771 --> 13:51.313
- Here, at Shibden.
[sighs]

13:51.396 --> 13:53.062
Not that anything's
been said yet.

13:53.146 --> 13:54.646
- But would she leave
Crow Nest?

13:54.730 --> 13:55.730
It's very elegant.

13:55.813 --> 13:57.688
- Shibden could be elegant.

13:57.771 --> 13:59.730
Shibden will be elegant.

14:00.563 --> 14:04.979
- You know I want you
to be happy, above all things,

14:05.062 --> 14:08.688
but her tribe
will have things to say.

14:08.771 --> 14:11.146
- What could be better
for them?

14:11.229 --> 14:12.146
Hmm?

14:12.229 --> 14:14.479
Two respectable landed ladies

14:14.563 --> 14:16.271
living together
as companions.

14:16.354 --> 14:19.354
They wouldn't have to worry
about her anymore, would they?

14:19.438 --> 14:23.187
She has 2 1/2 thousand a year,

14:23.271 --> 14:26.688
2 of it
entirely at her disposal.

14:26.771 --> 14:30.021
Wouldn't you say
that was a prudent match?

14:30.104 --> 14:32.979
- Yes, of course,

14:33.062 --> 14:35.271
if you were a man.

14:36.937 --> 14:39.855
[somber music]

14:39.937 --> 14:44.521
♪ ♪

14:44.605 --> 14:49.187
- Nature played
a challenging trick on me,

14:49.271 --> 14:51.605
didn't she,

14:51.688 --> 14:54.104
putting a bold spirit like mine

14:54.187 --> 14:55.688
in this vessel,

14:55.771 --> 14:57.563
in which I'm obliged

14:57.646 --> 14:58.896
to wear frills and petticoats?

14:58.979 --> 15:01.813
Well, I refuse
to be cowed by it.

15:01.896 --> 15:04.062
- People can be very cruel.

15:04.146 --> 15:05.813
- Shame on them.

15:05.896 --> 15:08.313
- I don't want you
to be hurt.

15:08.396 --> 15:10.062
- Sometimes,

15:10.146 --> 15:14.021
if we want to be happy,
we have to risk getting hurt.

15:14.104 --> 15:16.146
- This is Halifax.

15:16.229 --> 15:18.021
They don't mince words.

15:18.104 --> 15:20.313
♪ ♪

15:20.396 --> 15:22.563
- They can't touch me.

15:22.646 --> 15:28.313
♪ ♪

15:54.937 --> 15:56.771
- I bet you don't read
at the breakfast table

15:56.855 --> 15:59.937
when you're at Langton
with the Norcliffes,

16:00.021 --> 16:01.646
or when she's staying
at Lawton Hall

16:01.730 --> 16:05.062
with Mrs. Lawton,

16:05.146 --> 16:08.979
or when you were in Hastings
with Miss Hobart.

16:11.688 --> 16:16.688
- You're quite right, Marian,
of course.

16:16.771 --> 16:19.771
- I am anxious
that the whole thing

16:19.855 --> 16:22.062
hasn't been properly addressed.

16:22.146 --> 16:23.271
- I'm sorry.
The whole thing?

16:23.354 --> 16:25.313
- Anne has assured me
that in future,

16:25.396 --> 16:27.479
if she decides
to stay out later than usual,

16:27.563 --> 16:29.979
she'll write us a note
or tell us in advance.

16:30.062 --> 16:32.605
- It was only 10:00 when she
came in, though, wasn't it?

16:32.688 --> 16:34.813
- If we'd known
to expect her at 10:00,

16:34.896 --> 16:36.813
this would be
a very different conversation.

16:36.896 --> 16:38.146
- You see, you've heard
about people

16:38.229 --> 16:40.730
who get knocked about
and robbed.

16:40.813 --> 16:41.855
- As it wa--
- And worse.

16:41.937 --> 16:43.104
- As it was--
- She used to come in

16:43.187 --> 16:44.021
at all hours.

16:44.104 --> 16:45.646
- I had Cordingley
and Hemingway

16:45.730 --> 16:47.979
poised on the verge
of going out looking for her!

16:48.062 --> 16:50.146
- I found her once
at a lodging house

16:50.229 --> 16:52.688
in Halifax
at 3:00 in the morning,

16:52.771 --> 16:55.479
playing cards...
- It's too easy.

16:55.563 --> 16:57.646
- With a bunch of reprobates
from the 33rd.

16:57.730 --> 17:00.813
[laughs]

17:00.896 --> 17:02.229
- [sputters, coughs]

17:04.271 --> 17:06.146
Good Lord.

17:06.229 --> 17:08.855
That was a while since.

17:08.937 --> 17:11.688
- Perhaps she'd like
to apologize to the servants

17:11.771 --> 17:12.730
for keeping them up.

17:12.813 --> 17:15.104
- I'm not apologizing
to my own servants.

17:15.187 --> 17:17.354
No one asked them--
- The  servants.

17:17.438 --> 17:19.021
- Oh, it's about that.
Of course it is.

17:19.104 --> 17:20.730
- It's about respect
for other people--

17:20.813 --> 17:21.855
- Whatever it starts off as,

17:21.937 --> 17:23.396
it always comes back to that.

17:23.479 --> 17:25.688
- No, it doesn't!

17:25.771 --> 17:27.646
Well, why wouldn't it?

17:27.730 --> 17:29.521
Am I supposed
to take it lying down,

17:29.605 --> 17:31.187
the fact that my sister--

17:31.271 --> 17:34.062
you certainly wouldn't--
has cheated me

17:34.146 --> 17:35.396
out of what is
rightly half mine!

17:35.479 --> 17:36.563
- No, no, no, no, no.

17:36.646 --> 17:37.855
- You're going to have
to let this go, Marian,

17:37.937 --> 17:39.146
for your own health.

17:39.229 --> 17:40.313
It's becoming an obsession,

17:40.396 --> 17:42.521
and it was never
rightly half yours.

17:42.605 --> 17:44.563
It was entirely
at Uncle James' disposal

17:44.646 --> 17:46.313
who he left the estate to,

17:46.396 --> 17:47.730
and we all know
why he did.

17:47.813 --> 17:49.062
- I shall get married!

17:49.146 --> 17:50.730
I shall get married!
- Oh, really?

17:50.813 --> 17:51.896
Oh, good.

17:51.979 --> 17:54.187
- And I shall have a child--
yes, really--a son.

17:54.271 --> 17:55.855
- Congratulations.
- And one day, he will--

17:55.937 --> 17:57.187
- You better look sharp
about it, Marian...

17:57.271 --> 17:59.271
- You think I have no life
outside these four walls?

17:59.354 --> 18:01.187
- Because you're
no spring chicken.

18:01.271 --> 18:05.229
- Oh, you are sowing
the wind hourly, daily,

18:05.313 --> 18:06.605
minute by minute,

18:06.688 --> 18:08.730
and you will reap
the whirlwind!

18:08.813 --> 18:09.771
- Where are you going?

18:09.855 --> 18:11.187
You're not going to get married
right now,

18:11.271 --> 18:12.396
are you, Marian?

18:12.479 --> 18:13.730
Good heavens.
There's no stopping her.

18:13.813 --> 18:15.104
We better get
the banns read.

18:15.187 --> 18:17.021
- You can sneer
all you like,

18:17.104 --> 18:18.771
but one day,
I shall have a son,

18:18.855 --> 18:21.021
and he will have
a greater claim to Shibden

18:21.104 --> 18:23.187
than you, and then, then...

18:23.271 --> 18:25.563
then, we shall see!

18:25.646 --> 18:28.062
- You're going to give birth
to spite me?

18:28.146 --> 18:30.479
Well, I do hope this husband

18:30.563 --> 18:32.104
is someone worthy
of marrying my sister

18:32.187 --> 18:33.730
and fathering a Lister.

18:33.813 --> 18:35.896
- He won't be a Lister!

18:38.313 --> 18:39.229
- Hmm.

18:39.313 --> 18:42.021
- Rachel, I'd like you
to pack my imperial.

18:42.104 --> 18:43.813
I'm going to stay
with Mr. and Mrs. Dyson

18:43.896 --> 18:45.354
in Market Weighton
for a few weeks.

18:45.438 --> 18:47.271
I'll write ahead
and explain.

18:47.354 --> 18:49.979
- Now, ma'am?
- Yes, now!

18:50.062 --> 18:52.146
[jaunty music]

18:52.229 --> 18:53.229
- Morning.

18:53.313 --> 18:54.605
- Morning, ma'am.

18:54.688 --> 18:56.271
♪ ♪

18:56.354 --> 18:57.396
- Morning.

18:57.479 --> 18:58.730
- Morning, ma'am.

18:58.813 --> 19:00.855
- Thomas.
Dick.

19:00.937 --> 19:02.605
- Ma'am.
- Sowden.

19:02.688 --> 19:06.605
- Morning, ma'am.
[breaks wind]

19:06.688 --> 19:07.646
- Morning, Pickels.

19:07.730 --> 19:09.813
- Morning, missus.
- You made a start.

19:09.896 --> 19:11.313
- Cracking on
while the weather's with us.

19:11.396 --> 19:13.021
- I see you've got
Sam Sowden working for you.

19:13.104 --> 19:15.813
- Aye, well, uh, I needed
someone with a cart

19:15.896 --> 19:18.313
for stone, and the fella
I normally use

19:18.396 --> 19:19.396
is off on another job.

19:19.479 --> 19:20.937
- Is he pulling his weight?

19:21.021 --> 19:22.146
- Summat up, Bob?

19:22.229 --> 19:24.855
- Ah, no, you're right, Sam.

19:24.937 --> 19:26.563
- Has he been drinking?

19:26.646 --> 19:27.730
- I ha--I don't--

19:27.813 --> 19:29.187
- It's five-and-twenty
to 10:00 in the morning.

19:29.271 --> 19:30.479
- I don't think he's, uh--

19:30.563 --> 19:32.229
- Are you scared of him?
- How do you mean?

19:32.313 --> 19:33.563
- Then why are you
defending him?

19:33.646 --> 19:35.313
- As I say,
I needed a cart, so--

19:35.396 --> 19:36.646
- William Hardcastle
over at Roydelands

19:36.730 --> 19:37.896
has a good cart.
- Well, maybe,

19:37.979 --> 19:39.396
but this one's here now, so--
- You shall soon see

19:39.479 --> 19:40.855
this sort of thing
just doesn't do for me.

19:40.937 --> 19:42.313
Are you gonna say something,
or shall I?

19:42.396 --> 19:43.521
- Eh?
- Sowden!

19:43.605 --> 19:46.229
- Ah?
What's the matter?

19:46.313 --> 19:47.438
- You're not working for me
in that state.

19:47.521 --> 19:49.271
You'll have to go home.

19:49.354 --> 19:50.354
- What state?

19:50.438 --> 19:51.438
- I don't want to fall out
with you twice,

19:51.521 --> 19:52.896
but if I have to, I will.

19:52.979 --> 19:54.187
- What state?
- Don't deny it.

19:54.271 --> 19:55.521
You'll just dig yourself
deeper.

19:55.605 --> 19:57.021
Send one of your lads
over to Roydelands.

19:57.104 --> 19:59.062
Tell Hardcastle Miss Lister
will consider it a great favor

19:59.146 --> 20:00.146
if we could borrow his cart.

20:00.229 --> 20:01.396
Tell him I'll give him
two shillings

20:01.479 --> 20:03.062
on top of whatever
you've allocated for the job.

20:03.146 --> 20:04.354
- Hang on, hang on, hang on.

20:04.438 --> 20:05.730
What's she accusing me of?

20:05.813 --> 20:07.396
- You'd better get
off home, Sam.

20:07.479 --> 20:09.730
- She seri'sly suggesting
I come to work

20:09.813 --> 20:11.646
whatever time it is drunk?

20:11.730 --> 20:12.855
'cause if you are--
I mean, if she is,

20:12.937 --> 20:13.855
I don't care who she is.
I--

20:13.937 --> 20:15.021
- You're drunk, Sowden.

20:15.104 --> 20:16.187
Thomas, I want you
to take your father home,

20:16.271 --> 20:17.896
and then I want you
to come back.

20:17.979 --> 20:20.229
- A'ight.
- All right.

20:20.313 --> 20:23.021
Know what you are,
don't you, eh?

20:23.104 --> 20:24.855
Eh?
- Now, let's keep it polite.

20:24.937 --> 20:26.104
- She's a fella.
- Hey!

20:26.187 --> 20:27.229
Now get him off home now!

20:27.313 --> 20:28.688
- Fella in a frock.
- Hey, come on, Sam.

20:28.771 --> 20:30.313
- Ah, go on, go on,

20:30.396 --> 20:31.438
show us your cock.
Come on.

20:31.521 --> 20:33.104
- Stop it!
- Just calm down!

20:33.187 --> 20:34.855
- Mean, "ca--"?
- Come on, Sam.

20:34.937 --> 20:36.271
- I didn't start anything.
I don't--I don't--

20:36.354 --> 20:37.605
- Sam!
- All right, all right.

20:37.688 --> 20:38.855
How did we get here?

20:38.937 --> 20:41.688
- And tomorrow, Sowden--
are you listening to me?

20:41.771 --> 20:43.187
When you're sober,
if you're sober,

20:43.271 --> 20:44.646
I'd like you to come up
to the hall, and we can have

20:44.730 --> 20:46.229
a very quiet,
very thoughtful conversation

20:46.313 --> 20:49.062
about your tenancy.

20:49.146 --> 20:50.855
- [laughs]
You what?

20:50.937 --> 20:51.979
- Take him home.

20:52.062 --> 20:52.896
- Go with him.

20:52.979 --> 20:54.021
Make sure he gets him home.

20:54.104 --> 20:56.396
- [laughs]
Unbe--

20:56.479 --> 20:58.229
This is--
- Sit down.

20:58.313 --> 21:01.187
[tense music]

21:01.271 --> 21:02.896
- Didn't even do anything!

21:02.979 --> 21:09.438
♪ ♪

21:10.979 --> 21:12.521
- Idiot.

21:12.605 --> 21:15.646
- Lot of shouting
this morning,

21:15.730 --> 21:18.146
Marian and Anne.

21:18.229 --> 21:19.813
Can't think what about.

21:22.146 --> 21:23.896
I never really listen.

21:23.979 --> 21:25.937
Well, I can't hear...
[laughs]

21:26.021 --> 21:27.313
Which could be a blessing.

21:27.396 --> 21:29.396
- [laughs]

21:29.479 --> 21:33.021
- I-I remember
what it was.

21:33.104 --> 21:35.187
Oh.
Hail to the chief.

21:35.271 --> 21:36.855
- Mr. Rawson.
- Miss Lister.

21:36.937 --> 21:40.313
I'm sorry to hear you've had
a contretemps with your sister.

21:40.396 --> 21:41.646
- Oh, I don't think so.

21:41.730 --> 21:45.104
Marian and I rarely argue
about anything.

21:45.187 --> 21:47.271
Shall we be brief?

21:47.354 --> 21:50.605
- Well, I...

21:50.688 --> 21:52.438
I got your note
about the other party

21:52.521 --> 21:54.062
offering you your price.

21:54.146 --> 21:55.730
Um, I have to be frank.

21:55.813 --> 21:58.229
My brother and I are amazed.

21:58.313 --> 21:59.813
- Well, there you have it.

21:59.896 --> 22:01.813
If you want to better
the offer I've had,

22:01.896 --> 22:03.438
then now's your chance,
but as I said before,

22:03.521 --> 22:06.813
I remain indifferent
about selling my coals or not.

22:06.896 --> 22:09.771
- Well, I had naively thought

22:09.855 --> 22:12.062
that you might be
more reasonable to deal with.

22:12.146 --> 22:15.104
- More reasonable?

22:15.187 --> 22:16.313
Oh, you mean softer.

22:16.396 --> 22:18.187
- No, madam,
I meant more reasonable.

22:18.271 --> 22:20.521
- Well, now you know me better.

22:20.605 --> 22:22.354
I have heard
a good deal about coal

22:22.438 --> 22:24.104
in the last few days
and weeks,

22:24.187 --> 22:27.229
and rather than find me
easier to bargain with,

22:27.313 --> 22:29.104
I'm afraid now
you'll find me harder.

22:31.354 --> 22:34.438
So, £226,

22:34.521 --> 22:36.563
17 shillings and sixpence
per acre

22:36.646 --> 22:39.479
to be paid per annum in two
half-yearly installments,

22:39.563 --> 22:42.187
the first of which to be made
on signing the deed.

22:42.271 --> 22:44.354
You have ten years
to get the coal in.

22:44.438 --> 22:45.646
If not got in that time,

22:45.730 --> 22:48.605
I'll allow you a further term,
not exceeding five years.

22:49.605 --> 22:51.979
Oh, and if it causes you
no great upset,

22:52.062 --> 22:54.062
I'd like provision made
in the lease

22:54.146 --> 22:55.771
for me to go down
your Law Hill pit.

22:57.979 --> 22:59.771
- Why?
Why?

23:02.896 --> 23:04.813
- Because it fascinates me.

23:06.271 --> 23:08.229
You'll access the bed

23:08.313 --> 23:09.354
from your Law Hill pit,

23:09.438 --> 23:11.855
and I'd like to see it.
That's all.

23:11.937 --> 23:14.187
- Well,

23:14.271 --> 23:15.438
I'm sure it can be arranged,

23:15.521 --> 23:16.855
but it's hardly something

23:16.937 --> 23:18.396
to put in a lease.

23:18.479 --> 23:21.730
I have to talk to my--
my brother.

23:21.813 --> 23:23.146
- Of course you would.

23:23.229 --> 23:24.396
I have to go.

23:24.479 --> 23:26.979
I'll send a note to Mr. Parker
to draw up the lease.

23:27.062 --> 23:29.563
I've already been
through the details with him.

23:29.646 --> 23:32.146
And then he'll be in touch
with you about signing it.

23:33.605 --> 23:36.187
[jaunty music]

23:36.271 --> 23:38.438
[pigs squealing]

23:38.521 --> 23:45.605
♪ ♪

23:51.979 --> 23:53.187
- What's happened?

23:53.271 --> 23:55.229
- Nowt.

23:55.313 --> 23:56.855
Finished work
for the day.

23:56.937 --> 23:59.313
That's all.
- I thought--

23:59.396 --> 24:00.354
well, didn't Mr. Pickels say

24:00.438 --> 24:01.605
it were a couple weeks
of a job?

24:01.688 --> 24:05.479
- Yeah, it was.
It is.

24:05.563 --> 24:08.271
Right, I'm going back,
and I'm taking the cart.

24:08.354 --> 24:10.187
- You're going nowhere,
you little runt.

24:10.271 --> 24:11.396
Cart stays here.

24:11.479 --> 24:12.937
- I'm sick of being tarred
by the same brush as him.

24:13.021 --> 24:14.396
- Aren't they getting
Mr. Hardcastle's cart?

24:14.479 --> 24:15.937
- Yeah, well, they'll have two
if we take this one back.

24:16.021 --> 24:17.438
- You're going nowhere!

24:17.521 --> 24:19.271
Told you.

24:19.354 --> 24:20.605
You can piss off an' all.

24:20.688 --> 24:21.730
- [grunts]

24:21.813 --> 24:22.688
- What are you doing?

24:22.771 --> 24:24.730
- Off you trot!
[blows landing]

24:24.813 --> 24:26.438
- We're gonna get thrown
off farm,

24:26.521 --> 24:28.104
all 'cause he can't do
even part of a day's work

24:28.187 --> 24:29.104
without getting drunk

24:29.187 --> 24:33.937
and opening his stupid,
nasty mouth!

24:34.021 --> 24:35.937
- Gosh.
Sam, please don't!

24:36.021 --> 24:37.187
Please, leave him alone!

24:37.271 --> 24:38.646
Sam, stop it, please!
- Get off!

24:38.730 --> 24:40.104
- Leave him alone, please!

24:40.187 --> 24:41.646
Sam, leave him alone!

24:41.730 --> 24:42.688
Stop it!
- G--stop!

24:42.771 --> 24:44.062
- Leave him, Sam!
Don't!

24:44.146 --> 24:45.146
Please!
- You're gonna kill him!

24:45.229 --> 24:46.313
- Stop it!

24:46.396 --> 24:47.813
Sam, please, leave him alone!
- Squeak, piggy.

24:47.896 --> 24:48.937
Squeak!

24:49.021 --> 24:50.688
- Stop it!

24:50.771 --> 24:52.813
♪ ♪

24:52.896 --> 24:54.979
[Thomas coughing]

24:55.062 --> 24:55.979
♪ ♪

24:56.062 --> 24:57.521
- You stupid bitch.

24:58.605 --> 25:01.313
[grunting, fighting]

25:01.396 --> 25:03.646
♪ ♪

25:03.730 --> 25:06.979
- No!
No!

25:07.062 --> 25:09.479
- Get off me!
Get off me!

25:09.563 --> 25:11.563
Get off me, you--
- Alfie!

25:11.646 --> 25:12.813
Alfie, there's
a rope in t'cart!

25:12.896 --> 25:13.855
Get that rope!
Get it!

25:13.937 --> 25:14.937
- Get off!

25:15.021 --> 25:16.563
- Stop wriggling!
- Agh!

25:16.646 --> 25:17.813
- Stop wriggling, you pig!

25:17.896 --> 25:19.229
- You're a fucking bastard!

25:19.313 --> 25:21.813
- Shut your dirty mouth.

25:21.896 --> 25:23.146
- You better--

25:26.104 --> 25:27.688
- Anne--

25:27.771 --> 25:30.979
I think--

25:31.062 --> 25:31.979
- I'm afraid there's been

25:32.062 --> 25:33.354
a change of plan.
- Oh?

25:33.438 --> 25:35.438
- Well, nothing to do
with this, us, and all to do

25:35.521 --> 25:37.855
with Marian being ridiculous
and irritating.

25:37.937 --> 25:39.229
- Oh, dear.
- So--mm--

25:39.313 --> 25:42.062
bit of a bust-up, so she's off
to Market Weighton.

25:42.146 --> 25:43.062
- I'm sorry.

25:43.146 --> 25:45.021
- Huh?
Don't be.

25:45.104 --> 25:49.229
So--so I think we--

25:49.313 --> 25:52.479
Let's wait a day or two,

25:52.563 --> 25:55.229
let the dust settle,
and then--

25:55.313 --> 25:57.104
and then we'll pay your call
on my aunt.

25:57.187 --> 26:00.271
- But you'll still come to me
for dinner this evening?

26:00.354 --> 26:02.896
- Of course.
- And stay all night?

26:04.979 --> 26:07.146
- Ah...
- [laughs]

26:08.646 --> 26:11.813
- They had to send for a doctor
last night for my aunt.

26:11.896 --> 26:14.896
Now, with her--madam--
going off to Market Weighton,

26:14.979 --> 26:16.563
it would look very bad

26:16.646 --> 26:18.354
if I left her
with just the servants

26:18.438 --> 26:19.730
all night.

26:19.813 --> 26:22.229
Sorry.
It's...

26:22.313 --> 26:24.313
bad timing, I know,

26:24.396 --> 26:28.771
but... I will still come
to dinner,

26:28.855 --> 26:31.146
and stay for a little while,
if that's...

26:31.229 --> 26:33.813
- [chuckles]

26:33.896 --> 26:36.354
- And then, another time,

26:36.438 --> 26:40.146
when the dust's settled...

26:40.229 --> 26:43.021
and soon, we can--
- I'd like that.

26:44.813 --> 26:48.438
Um, there was
something else

26:48.521 --> 26:51.771
I wanted to, um...

26:51.855 --> 26:52.979
tell you.

26:53.062 --> 26:55.271
[jaunty music]

26:55.354 --> 26:57.187
I've had a letter.

26:57.271 --> 27:00.479
It's about you.

27:00.563 --> 27:05.271
♪ ♪

27:05.354 --> 27:06.688
- Married?

27:06.771 --> 27:10.730
- Apparently, so would you
tell Caligula?

27:10.813 --> 27:12.479
- Well, Eugénie
speaks no English,

27:12.563 --> 27:14.271
and he surely doesn't
speak any French.

27:14.354 --> 27:16.354
- I agreed to be
the messenger.

27:16.438 --> 27:18.563
Anne will no doubt
get to the nub of it,

27:18.646 --> 27:20.688
effortlessly
and in her own manner.

27:20.771 --> 27:22.521
- Oh, I wish you and Anne
wouldn't argue.

27:22.605 --> 27:25.563
- She's the one that--
- I know, I know.

27:25.646 --> 27:30.062
Eh, might you get married?

27:30.146 --> 27:31.855
Is there someone?

27:38.396 --> 27:42.646
- I have twice
been invited to tea

27:42.730 --> 27:44.062
at Dr. and Mrs. Kenny's

27:44.146 --> 27:48.688
when Mr. John Abbott
has been invited, too, and...

27:48.771 --> 27:53.104
he and I have become,
well, friendly.

27:53.187 --> 27:56.937
- John Abbott?
- Yes.

27:57.021 --> 28:01.771
- Is he not something
in wool?

28:01.855 --> 28:05.479
- Yes, but he's also
a founder member

28:05.563 --> 28:08.354
of the Halifax
Joint Stock Banking Company,

28:08.438 --> 28:12.646
and he owns property
in Australia and New Zealand.

28:12.730 --> 28:14.688
Nothing's been said,

28:14.771 --> 28:16.771
but he has intimated
to Mrs. Kenny

28:16.855 --> 28:20.313
that he's, well...

28:20.396 --> 28:22.937
really rather fond of me.

28:23.021 --> 28:25.521
Anyway, look,

28:25.605 --> 28:27.688
I shan't be gone
for more than two weeks,

28:27.771 --> 28:30.896
and if you need me, write.

28:30.979 --> 28:33.146
I'll come straight back.

28:35.313 --> 28:37.646
Oh, and please,

28:37.730 --> 28:41.021
don't tell Anne
about Mr. Abbott.

28:41.104 --> 28:42.937
I shouldn't have said
what I said this morning,

28:43.021 --> 28:47.855
but she just makes me so cross!

28:47.937 --> 28:48.979
[sighs]

28:49.062 --> 28:52.062
[melancholy music]

28:52.146 --> 28:55.521
♪ ♪

28:55.605 --> 28:59.104
- Are you all right?

28:59.187 --> 29:03.396
- This is written by someone
who knows nothing about me.

29:03.479 --> 29:07.771
It's so poisonous.
It's so cowardly.

29:07.855 --> 29:09.855
- I suppose it wasn't meant
for your eyes,

29:09.937 --> 29:12.896
but... I wanted you
to see it,

29:12.979 --> 29:15.855
because I wanted you to know

29:15.937 --> 29:19.396
that I don't care
what anyone says about you,

29:19.479 --> 29:21.771
not least someone
who daren't even put their name

29:21.855 --> 29:23.937
to their work.

29:24.021 --> 29:31.104
♪ ♪

29:37.605 --> 29:41.396
- Got to go
see how my aunt is.

29:41.479 --> 29:43.771
I'll see you this evening.

29:43.855 --> 29:47.605
♪ ♪

29:47.688 --> 29:49.937
Can I take this?

29:50.021 --> 29:51.271
- Mm.

29:51.354 --> 29:58.062
♪ ♪

29:58.146 --> 30:00.104
James,

30:00.187 --> 30:02.021
were you riding on the back
of Miss Walker's carriage

30:02.104 --> 30:03.479
the other week,
when that accident happened

30:03.563 --> 30:05.354
above my house?
- Yes, ma'am.

30:05.438 --> 30:07.104
- So you were facing
the gig, then?

30:07.187 --> 30:10.187
As I understand it, the gig
that forced its way through

30:10.271 --> 30:11.271
and caused all the bother.

30:11.354 --> 30:12.937
- Yes, ma'am.

30:13.021 --> 30:14.771
- The boy lost a leg.

30:14.896 --> 30:18.563
Any information
would be useful.

30:18.646 --> 30:21.979
- Well, the only thing:

30:22.062 --> 30:23.896
after it all happened,

30:23.979 --> 30:25.979
William Bell, our groom,

30:26.062 --> 30:28.646
said he could swear blind

30:28.730 --> 30:32.062
that the driver was
Mr. Rawson himself.

30:32.146 --> 30:35.104
[dark music]

30:35.187 --> 30:41.605
♪ ♪

30:43.229 --> 30:45.855
- It's Mr. Rawson,
Mr. Parker.

30:45.937 --> 30:48.979
♪ ♪

30:49.062 --> 30:51.104
- Mr. Parker.
- Mr. Rawson.

30:51.187 --> 30:52.937
- There's a problem.

30:53.021 --> 30:54.813
- I have come to terms, Parker,

30:54.896 --> 30:56.688
with Miss Lister's
ridiculous price,

30:56.771 --> 30:58.354
and I will even sign to say

30:58.438 --> 30:59.896
she can go down
my Law Hill pit,

30:59.979 --> 31:01.563
under certain conditions,

31:01.646 --> 31:03.605
so surely now--
- It's--

31:03.688 --> 31:05.479
there's this other thing.

31:05.563 --> 31:07.187
[sighs]
I had assumed

31:07.271 --> 31:08.813
that we were talking
about the upper bed

31:08.896 --> 31:10.937
and the lower bed
for the named price,

31:11.021 --> 31:13.104
but here, it seems

31:13.187 --> 31:14.688
that we're buying
just the lower bed,

31:14.771 --> 31:16.605
and that is the richest seam,

31:16.688 --> 31:19.354
but obviously,
it's the upper bed we're...

31:19.438 --> 31:21.605
interested in as well.

31:23.271 --> 31:24.813
- Has your client
any real intention

31:24.896 --> 31:27.104
of sealing this deal,
Mr. Parker,

31:27.187 --> 31:30.021
or is she just playing
some impenetrable game,

31:30.104 --> 31:32.396
the point of which
is to vex me?

31:32.479 --> 31:34.354
We're men of business.

31:34.438 --> 31:35.979
We like to shake hands
and move forward,

31:36.062 --> 31:37.521
not jump through endless hoops

31:37.605 --> 31:40.563
of her whimsical, idiotic,
and ill-informed construction.

31:40.646 --> 31:41.771
- I think of all the criticisms

31:41.855 --> 31:45.021
one might level at Miss Lister,
that, um,

31:45.104 --> 31:48.396
"whimsical, idiotic,
and ill-informed"

31:48.479 --> 31:50.313
are rather wide of the mark.

31:52.813 --> 31:55.354
- Was this not clarified
in all these conversations

31:55.438 --> 31:57.688
you've been having with her?

31:57.771 --> 31:59.646
- I was talking
about whole surface measure,

31:59.730 --> 32:01.229
which normally would mean
the upper bed

32:01.313 --> 32:02.354
and the lower bed.

32:02.438 --> 32:04.730
She has specified
in this lease

32:04.813 --> 32:05.771
"sufficient measure,"

32:05.855 --> 32:07.979
which, when you read it
closely,

32:08.062 --> 32:10.479
she's talking
just about the lower bed.

32:13.688 --> 32:17.896
- Both beds, or no deal.

32:17.979 --> 32:20.313
Your client, Mr. Parker,

32:20.396 --> 32:23.104
needs to learn to stop
wasting my time.

32:23.187 --> 32:25.688
Perhaps you could spell that
out to her.

32:26.688 --> 32:29.146
[dark music]

32:29.229 --> 32:31.605
Welly!
[dog barks]

32:31.688 --> 32:38.730
♪ ♪

33:25.146 --> 33:27.479
- He's messed his pants.
- Has he?

33:27.563 --> 33:30.229
- He offered me sixpence
to untie him.

33:30.313 --> 33:32.104
- He hasn't got sixpence.

33:32.187 --> 33:34.479
- No, I know.

33:34.563 --> 33:37.813
- Mr. Pickels was grateful
to have the cart back,

33:37.896 --> 33:39.730
you'll be thrilled to learn.

33:42.730 --> 33:45.021
- You'd better untie me.

33:45.104 --> 33:46.563
- How do we know
you won't start throwing

33:46.646 --> 33:48.479
your weight around again?

33:50.771 --> 33:54.146
- Someone comes along here
and finds me like this,

33:54.229 --> 33:56.313
you ain't gonna last
two minutes, lad.

33:56.396 --> 33:58.813
- Thing is, no one ever does
come out here,

33:58.896 --> 34:00.688
do they?

34:00.771 --> 34:02.646
I mean, not out here.

34:02.730 --> 34:04.979
Nobody visits us, do they?

34:05.062 --> 34:07.187
'Cause nobody likes us.

34:07.271 --> 34:11.021
- Miss Lister is expecting me
at the hall tomorrow.

34:11.104 --> 34:12.271
I mean, you think she ain't
gonna come

34:12.354 --> 34:14.855
snooping around here
if I don't turn up, huh?

34:14.937 --> 34:16.271
Aye.

34:16.354 --> 34:18.229
Never thought about that,
did you?

34:18.313 --> 34:19.771
Elsie.

34:32.187 --> 34:35.104
[uneasy music]

34:35.187 --> 34:37.062
♪ ♪

34:37.146 --> 34:38.605
- Amy!

34:38.688 --> 34:45.688
♪ ♪

34:51.313 --> 34:52.605
[knocking at door]

34:52.688 --> 34:53.937
[door opens]

34:55.104 --> 34:56.646
- A note just arrived, ma'am,

34:56.730 --> 34:58.813
from Mr. Jeremiah Rawson's
servant.

35:06.688 --> 35:09.771
- Madam, I am at a loss
to account

35:09.855 --> 35:12.271
for the misunderstanding
between us.

35:12.354 --> 35:13.979
I considered
by "sufficient measure,"

35:14.062 --> 35:15.937
you meant both the lower
and upper bed,

35:16.021 --> 35:17.646
and that was
the only consideration

35:17.730 --> 35:20.896
that induced me to offer
such an enormous price.

35:22.521 --> 35:24.229
- I'm off.

35:24.313 --> 35:26.438
10:00.
- I'm going to send John.

35:26.521 --> 35:28.021
- You're not going
to send John.

35:28.104 --> 35:29.021
- I'm going to send John.

35:29.104 --> 35:30.605
I do not like you
walking home alone.

35:30.688 --> 35:32.605
- Fine, send John,
but tell him not to arrive

35:32.688 --> 35:34.104
any earlier than 9:35.

35:34.187 --> 35:36.646
- You cannot walk back
from Lightcliffe in 25 minutes.

35:36.730 --> 35:38.771
- I can walk anywhere
in 25 minutes.

35:38.855 --> 35:40.271
- Well, John can't!

35:40.354 --> 35:42.896
- Well, then, I shall be
approximately five minutes

35:42.979 --> 35:45.021
later than 10:00,
and only because of John.

35:45.104 --> 35:46.937
Try not to lose
any more colonies, Captain.

35:47.021 --> 35:48.937
- What'd she say?
- Nothing.

35:49.021 --> 35:52.813
- Where's she going?
- John, just to warn you,

35:52.896 --> 35:54.646
is getting married.

35:54.730 --> 35:55.813
- John?

35:55.896 --> 35:57.896
- We'll have
this conversation later.

35:57.979 --> 35:58.979
- This John?
Our John?

35:59.062 --> 36:00.688
Who to?
- And, um--

36:00.771 --> 36:01.979
- Who's John
getting married to?

36:02.062 --> 36:04.187
- There's something worse.
Well, not--

36:04.271 --> 36:05.771
- Worse?

36:06.979 --> 36:08.479
- Um, Marian.

36:08.563 --> 36:09.979
- Marian?

36:10.062 --> 36:12.563
Marian's getting married?
Who to?

36:12.646 --> 36:13.937
Not to John, I trust--

36:14.021 --> 36:15.896
or maybe they are.
What do I know?

36:15.979 --> 36:17.730
Marian.
Does Marian even--

36:19.229 --> 36:20.979
Really?

36:21.062 --> 36:22.896
Marian's getting married?
- No, no, no.

36:22.979 --> 36:24.313
- Who is John
getting married to?

36:24.396 --> 36:27.396
- Look, I said
I wouldn't say anything.

36:27.479 --> 36:29.271
I want you to have
a nice evening,

36:29.354 --> 36:32.730
so off you pop, and we'll talk
about this later.

36:34.021 --> 36:36.979
[tranquil music]

36:37.062 --> 36:39.313
♪ ♪

36:39.396 --> 36:40.605
- No, we set off
at 5:00 a.m.

36:40.688 --> 36:42.354
We didn't get back
until 20 past midnight.

36:42.438 --> 36:43.354
- No!

36:43.438 --> 36:45.313
- I'm afraid I tired
my poor friend,

36:45.396 --> 36:46.688
Miss McLaine, out.

36:46.771 --> 36:49.187
Not a morsel of food
to eat all day,

36:49.271 --> 36:51.062
but yes,
I'd quite happily spend

36:51.146 --> 36:52.521
so much more time
in the highlands.

36:52.605 --> 36:55.605
- [laughs]
Oh, I had a letter,

36:55.688 --> 36:57.021
um, earlier this evening,

36:57.104 --> 36:59.979
from my friend,
Mrs. Ainsworth.

37:00.062 --> 37:01.979
I think I told you
about them this morning.

37:02.062 --> 37:06.354
Um, it turns out that he--
Mr. Ainsworth--

37:06.438 --> 37:09.229
has applied for a position
as clerk

37:09.313 --> 37:11.187
at the Lightcliffe church,

37:11.271 --> 37:13.979
and he has a meeting--
interview--

37:14.062 --> 37:15.979
the week after next
with the trustees,

37:16.062 --> 37:17.896
so they want to come
and stay then

37:17.979 --> 37:19.855
instead of January, and...

37:19.937 --> 37:21.396
Well, I know you said
you wanted to wait

37:21.479 --> 37:23.062
until after February to travel

37:23.146 --> 37:24.937
because of your aunt,
but the p--

37:25.021 --> 37:26.062
[both laugh]

37:26.146 --> 37:28.896
The point is,
from my point of view,

37:28.979 --> 37:31.062
we could be off sooner.

37:31.146 --> 37:33.730
[both laugh]

37:33.813 --> 37:38.313
♪ ♪

37:38.396 --> 37:42.104
- I wanted
to ask you something.

37:42.187 --> 37:43.896
I wanted to ask,

37:43.979 --> 37:46.438
when we come back
from the Continent,

37:46.521 --> 37:49.605
whether...
[laughs]

37:55.146 --> 37:58.937
You see, the thing is,
I shall never get married,

37:59.021 --> 38:00.438
ever,

38:00.521 --> 38:01.646
and if you felt

38:01.730 --> 38:06.479
that you might never
get married either...

38:06.563 --> 38:07.855
and you were prepared
to give up

38:07.937 --> 38:12.229
all thought
of ever having children,

38:12.313 --> 38:14.771
I wondered if,

38:14.855 --> 38:18.104
on our return,

38:18.187 --> 38:21.479
might we not live together,

38:21.563 --> 38:23.688
set up home together,

38:23.771 --> 38:24.937
as companions?

38:25.021 --> 38:27.605
- [moans]

38:27.688 --> 38:31.646
It'd be like a marriage.

38:31.730 --> 38:33.937
- Quite as good,

38:34.021 --> 38:36.521
or better.

38:36.605 --> 38:38.438
- [laughs]

38:41.646 --> 38:44.313
I do wonder, though.

38:44.396 --> 38:47.146
You see, I think I told you

38:47.229 --> 38:51.479
that I've always been
very fond of children,

38:51.563 --> 38:56.021
and whilst... giving birth

38:56.104 --> 38:59.396
isn't something that I'd want

38:59.479 --> 39:02.813
and whilst I always thought
that I would never marry,

39:02.896 --> 39:04.855
I did at one time

39:04.937 --> 39:08.813
feel an inclination
not to keep to that,

39:08.896 --> 39:11.979
so...

39:12.062 --> 39:15.896
it's difficult
to positively say

39:15.979 --> 39:20.688
that I might never feel
that same inclination again.

39:20.771 --> 39:21.813
- Oh.

39:23.271 --> 39:26.229
- So rather than give you
a yes now,

39:26.313 --> 39:29.688
could we wait six months?

39:29.771 --> 39:31.396
- Six months?

39:31.479 --> 39:36.313
- Well, it is, is it not,

39:36.396 --> 39:38.937
the same as a proposal,

39:39.021 --> 39:40.813
and would it not be prudent

39:40.896 --> 39:43.730
in any--in all circumstances

39:43.813 --> 39:47.313
for both parties
to fully consider

39:47.396 --> 39:48.855
everything that--

39:48.937 --> 39:51.229
- Of course.

39:51.313 --> 39:52.979
[tender music]

39:53.062 --> 39:56.479
Of course it would.

39:56.563 --> 40:00.062
It is exactly like a proposal,

40:00.146 --> 40:04.229
and six months is April.

40:04.313 --> 40:07.104
Shall we say the third?
It's my birthday.

40:07.187 --> 40:10.563
- Is it?
- Mm.

40:10.646 --> 40:14.271
I can wait that long,

40:14.354 --> 40:17.855
as long as I have reason
to hope.

40:17.937 --> 40:20.062
- Oh, I--

40:20.146 --> 40:23.354
I think you have
every reason to hope.

40:23.438 --> 40:30.479
♪ ♪

40:38.855 --> 40:40.521
[knocking]

40:40.605 --> 40:42.438
♪ ♪

40:42.521 --> 40:45.104
- Evening.
I'm calling for Miss Lister.

40:45.187 --> 40:46.605
- Who is it, Harry?

40:46.688 --> 40:48.146
- It's only me, Mr. Priestley.

40:48.229 --> 40:50.146
John Booth, from Shibden Hall.

40:50.229 --> 40:51.271
- Oh.

40:51.354 --> 40:53.313
What can we do for you, John?

40:53.396 --> 40:55.813
- Well, I've come
for Miss Lister.

40:55.896 --> 40:57.521
- Miss Lister?

40:57.605 --> 40:58.771
- To walk her back.

40:58.855 --> 40:59.771
- Hello, John.

40:59.855 --> 41:01.062
- Hello, Mrs. Priestley.

41:01.146 --> 41:03.104
- Miss Lister isn't here.

41:03.187 --> 41:05.146
- Oh, uh, she's set off?

41:05.229 --> 41:07.771
- No, she's not been here
since, uh--

41:07.855 --> 41:08.937
when was Anne here?

41:09.021 --> 41:10.813
- Uh, Tuesday.

41:10.896 --> 41:12.229
- Oh, was she not here
last night

41:12.313 --> 41:13.896
or the night before that?

41:15.855 --> 41:17.646
I've come to the wrong house.

41:17.730 --> 41:19.313
[sighs]
They said Lightcliffe,

41:19.396 --> 41:21.313
so I assumed...

41:21.396 --> 41:23.313
Oh, I am sorry.
I've disturbed you.

41:23.396 --> 41:26.313
- Don't worry, John.
- Well, where is she, then?

41:26.396 --> 41:28.646
- Well, happen
she's at Miss Walker's.

41:28.730 --> 41:31.521
[sauntering music]

41:31.605 --> 41:38.062
- Surely you care enough
about me to say yes.

41:38.146 --> 41:40.271
You do realize
you'll break my heart now

41:40.354 --> 41:42.438
if you say no.

41:42.521 --> 41:47.521
♪ ♪

41:47.605 --> 41:49.271
- [moans]

41:49.354 --> 41:51.730
♪ ♪

41:51.813 --> 41:53.979
Wait, stop.

41:54.062 --> 41:55.104
- Sorry, what?

41:55.187 --> 41:56.438
- It's--

41:56.521 --> 42:00.104
it's just too much.
It's too soon.

42:00.187 --> 42:01.479
- Did I hurt you?

42:01.563 --> 42:04.104
- No, it's not that.
It's--

42:04.187 --> 42:06.855
it's too soon.
I'm not...

42:06.937 --> 42:08.896
- Not what?

42:08.979 --> 42:10.937
- I don't know.

42:17.187 --> 42:19.354
- Does it feel wrong?

42:19.438 --> 42:21.521
- No--

42:21.605 --> 42:24.646
Not the kissing,
but just th-this.

42:24.730 --> 42:27.688
I just...
I don't know.

42:27.771 --> 42:29.396
I'm sorry.
- Sorry.

42:29.479 --> 42:32.896
No, I'm sorry.

42:32.979 --> 42:35.187
- Have I spoiled everything?

42:35.271 --> 42:36.979
- No.

42:37.062 --> 42:39.605
- I just--I--

42:39.688 --> 42:41.062
I've never done this before,

42:41.146 --> 42:44.438
and probably not
very good at it.

42:44.521 --> 42:48.104
I don't want
to disappoint you.

42:48.187 --> 42:50.937
- You haven't.

42:51.021 --> 42:54.271
You haven't.

42:54.354 --> 42:55.605
Ann...

42:55.688 --> 42:57.229
[bell rings]

42:57.313 --> 43:00.479
- Oh.
That'll be John.

43:00.563 --> 43:02.563
- Have you done this before?

43:02.646 --> 43:04.229
- No,

43:04.313 --> 43:05.688
of course not.

43:07.605 --> 43:09.688
- What are you looking at?

43:09.771 --> 43:11.062
- What?
[door opens]

43:11.146 --> 43:14.187
- Hmm?
- Nothing.

43:14.271 --> 43:15.855
[laughs]

43:15.937 --> 43:18.062
[jaunty music]

43:18.146 --> 43:21.563
- Ma'am, so did, um,

43:21.646 --> 43:22.855
did anyone talk to you

43:22.937 --> 43:25.021
about me and--and--

43:25.104 --> 43:27.187
- You and...
- Eugénie.

43:27.271 --> 43:28.979
- No.
- Oh.

43:29.062 --> 43:31.313
- My aunt said
you were getting married.

43:31.396 --> 43:33.229
Who to?

43:36.229 --> 43:37.896
Not Eugénie.

43:40.187 --> 43:42.271
No.

43:42.354 --> 43:44.813
Really?

43:44.896 --> 43:49.271
- She--we--
- How?

43:49.354 --> 43:52.271
No, seriously, how?

43:52.354 --> 43:54.438
You don't even speak
the same language.

43:54.521 --> 43:57.855
You have no French.
She barely speaks any English.

43:57.937 --> 44:00.146
- No, but love is blind.

44:00.229 --> 44:01.937
- Rubbish.

44:02.021 --> 44:05.062
Love needs language
to express itself.

44:05.146 --> 44:08.479
At a normal, prosaic level,
marriage is a legal agreement

44:08.563 --> 44:11.479
that can't be negotiated
by just gazing at someone.

44:11.563 --> 44:14.229
- Well, Mrs. Cordingley
has a smattering, as you know--

44:14.313 --> 44:16.937
she was your lady's maid
for a time--

44:17.021 --> 44:20.396
and yes, she's been very kind.

44:33.896 --> 44:35.062
- [sighs]

44:35.146 --> 44:38.813
It's not often
I'm speechless, John!

44:38.896 --> 44:41.605
- No.

44:41.688 --> 44:44.187
- Well,

44:44.271 --> 44:46.354
I'm not sure it's something

44:46.438 --> 44:48.855
I can give my consent to,

44:48.937 --> 44:51.104
not very readily, anyway...

44:52.605 --> 44:54.271
not that I would ever wish
to get in the way

44:54.354 --> 44:56.813
of someone's happiness,
obviously.

44:56.896 --> 44:58.479
- No, ma'am.

45:00.896 --> 45:04.187
- Well...

45:04.271 --> 45:06.313
I shall speak to her.

45:06.396 --> 45:07.896
- Very good, ma'am.

45:07.979 --> 45:10.354
Oh, there was summat else.

45:10.438 --> 45:12.646
Miss Lister, it was just--
- Keep up.

45:12.730 --> 45:14.896
- I went to New House just now

45:14.979 --> 45:17.354
first, instead of Crow Nest.

45:17.438 --> 45:20.187
Well, your aunt
said Lightcliffe, so--

45:20.271 --> 45:23.271
and I assumed wrongly
that you were

45:23.354 --> 45:25.354
with Mr. and Mrs. Priestley,

45:25.438 --> 45:27.855
so I disturbed them.

45:27.937 --> 45:29.688
I did apologize to them.

45:29.771 --> 45:32.104
Uh, they were
very polite about it,

45:32.187 --> 45:35.730
but, uh, so--yeah.

45:35.813 --> 45:38.730
[ominous music]

45:38.813 --> 45:43.479
♪ ♪

45:43.563 --> 45:45.896
- Help me!
Help me!

45:45.979 --> 45:52.396
[shouting]

45:52.479 --> 45:59.479
♪ ♪

46:04.313 --> 46:07.062
- Morning.

46:07.146 --> 46:08.104
- Help me.

46:08.187 --> 46:09.229
Help me!

46:09.313 --> 46:10.813
Come on, help me!

46:10.896 --> 46:14.605
Help me!
Help! Help!

46:14.688 --> 46:18.396
Help!
Agh!

46:18.479 --> 46:22.271
♪ ♪

46:22.354 --> 46:25.896
- Yeah, I wish I could believe
you've learned a lesson,

46:25.979 --> 46:28.646
but I'm scared you haven't.

46:28.730 --> 46:31.730
See, I'm scared
you never will.

46:31.813 --> 46:34.146
Can you see that this
isn't the way to live,

46:34.229 --> 46:35.771
where everyone who should
mean something to you

46:35.855 --> 46:38.479
is frightened of you every time
you walk into a room,

46:38.563 --> 46:39.937
every time they hear
your voice?

46:40.021 --> 46:41.979
Can you see that?

46:42.062 --> 46:45.771
- [panting]
- Eh?

46:45.855 --> 46:48.104
Just say something.

46:48.187 --> 46:49.771
Come on, just say something
that makes me think

46:49.855 --> 46:51.313
you've learned a lesson.

46:51.396 --> 46:54.396
- [continues seething]

46:54.479 --> 47:01.563
♪ ♪

47:10.104 --> 47:13.021
[pants]

47:13.104 --> 47:16.937
♪ ♪

47:17.021 --> 47:18.521
- John Abbott?

47:18.605 --> 47:20.896
- She's been to tea twice
at the Kennys'

47:20.979 --> 47:22.855
whilst Mr. Abbott was there.
That's all.

47:22.937 --> 47:26.396
- He makes carpets,
John Abbott.

47:26.479 --> 47:28.313
- Wool, yes, probably.

47:28.396 --> 47:30.979
- Either way,
he's trade through and through.

47:31.062 --> 47:32.688
- I said I wouldn't
say anything.

47:32.771 --> 47:33.730
- You're going to have
to put the tin lid

47:33.813 --> 47:35.646
on that one, Captain.
- Mm.

47:35.730 --> 47:36.937
- Otherwise, I will.

47:37.021 --> 47:39.187
- Ooh, I'm going to get
into trouble now.

47:39.271 --> 47:40.855
They were only
having tea together.

47:40.937 --> 47:41.855
- Twice.

47:41.937 --> 47:44.730
I'm off to check
on the men.

47:44.813 --> 47:45.937
Nonsense.

47:46.021 --> 47:48.021
You've done the right thing.

47:48.104 --> 47:49.771
Marian has no judgment.

47:49.855 --> 47:51.896
She always needs a steer
in the right direction,

47:51.979 --> 47:53.313
but better coming
from you, Father,

47:53.396 --> 47:54.396
rather than me.

47:54.479 --> 47:55.896
You know
how ridiculous she gets.

47:55.979 --> 48:00.521
When she comes back,
if she comes back.

48:00.605 --> 48:03.146
- Marian should get married.

48:03.229 --> 48:05.021
Do her good.

48:05.104 --> 48:07.479
Who cares if he's trade?

48:07.563 --> 48:09.563
If he has enough money
and he cares about her,

48:09.646 --> 48:12.521
and they can make
a life of it together...

48:12.605 --> 48:15.605
The world's moving forward,

48:15.688 --> 48:18.021
even if she isn't.

48:18.104 --> 48:20.646
[scoffs]

48:20.730 --> 48:22.855
[tranquil music]

48:22.937 --> 48:26.396
- I might pop in at Crow Nest.

48:26.479 --> 48:28.521
Do you imagine she's ill--

48:28.605 --> 48:29.979
Miss Walker--

48:30.062 --> 48:31.271
if Miss Lister's
been round there

48:31.354 --> 48:33.396
several nights in a row?

48:33.479 --> 48:35.979
- It's one possibility.

48:36.062 --> 48:38.313
- I might pop in.

48:38.396 --> 48:40.605
I don't want
to be a busybody...

48:40.688 --> 48:43.229
♪ ♪

48:43.313 --> 48:45.771
But I might pop in.

48:45.855 --> 48:51.896
♪ ♪

48:51.979 --> 48:55.104
- Did you have any more trouble
with Sam Sowden yesterday?

48:55.187 --> 48:56.521
- No, ma'am.

48:56.605 --> 48:57.688
Uh, Thomas brought
the cart back,

48:57.771 --> 48:59.062
and then he worked
like a trooper.

48:59.146 --> 49:01.563
- Good.
Thomas?

49:01.646 --> 49:03.396
- Come on, lad.

49:06.438 --> 49:07.688
- Morning, Miss Lister.

49:07.771 --> 49:09.021
- Will you--
[sighs]

49:09.104 --> 49:10.354
Good morning.

49:10.438 --> 49:12.521
Will you remind your father
I'd like to see him today

49:12.605 --> 49:15.021
up at the hall?
- Yes, ma'am.

49:15.104 --> 49:16.146
- And if he doesn't
come see me,

49:16.229 --> 49:17.271
I shall go and see him,

49:17.354 --> 49:18.771
and he'll like the consequences
even less

49:18.855 --> 49:21.271
if it comes to that.
- Yes, ma'am.

49:21.354 --> 49:23.021
- And Thomas, tell him
I appreciate him

49:23.104 --> 49:25.937
letting you bring
the cart back.

49:26.021 --> 49:27.605
- Uh, I can't just--
sorry, ma'am.

49:27.688 --> 49:30.771
The thing is...

49:30.855 --> 49:32.396
I can work hard,

49:32.479 --> 49:35.479
even if me father
isn't inclined, and...

49:35.563 --> 49:37.104
It'd be very hard
on me mother

49:37.187 --> 49:39.271
and the little ones if--

49:39.354 --> 49:42.021
if we were
to lose the farm.

49:42.104 --> 49:44.771
- Yes, but the problem is,
Thomas,

49:44.855 --> 49:46.146
my agreement is with him,

49:46.229 --> 49:47.479
and he and I need
to be better friends,

49:47.563 --> 49:49.479
and he needs
to accept my authority,

49:49.563 --> 49:53.646
or the whole thing
just doesn't work.

49:53.730 --> 49:55.313
[uneasy music]

49:55.396 --> 49:57.479
I'll be back later.
- Yes, ma'am.

49:57.563 --> 49:59.438
♪ ♪

49:59.521 --> 50:02.688
Come on back to work, lad.

50:02.771 --> 50:05.146
- Uh, can I nip out,
Mr. Pickels?

50:05.229 --> 50:07.771
I can leave cart here.
Only if I don't remind him,

50:07.855 --> 50:09.813
he won't turn up.

50:09.896 --> 50:13.646
♪ ♪

50:13.730 --> 50:15.646
- Is she--
- Yes, ma'am.

50:15.730 --> 50:22.771
♪ ♪

50:24.187 --> 50:25.438
- Ann?

50:25.521 --> 50:28.479
- I'm so glad you're here.

50:28.563 --> 50:29.813
- What's happened?

50:29.896 --> 50:32.187
- Nothing.
It's just,

50:32.271 --> 50:34.937
after last night,
I didn't think you'd come back.

50:37.396 --> 50:39.271
- Ah.

50:41.605 --> 50:45.354
You'll find me
a lot more constant than that.

50:45.438 --> 50:47.979
- I don't deserve you.
[sniffs]

50:48.062 --> 50:50.605
I'm not good enough for you.

50:50.688 --> 50:53.479
You're so clever
and interesting.

50:53.563 --> 50:55.396
You'll soon get fed up with me.

50:55.479 --> 50:56.563
- Ann, you've got
to stop having

50:56.646 --> 50:59.855
such a poor opinion
of yourself.

50:59.937 --> 51:02.438
Hmm?

51:02.521 --> 51:05.062
You're clever,

51:05.146 --> 51:08.021
and you're interesting.

51:08.104 --> 51:11.062
- Do you still want us
to live together?

51:11.146 --> 51:13.062
- Need you ask?

51:13.146 --> 51:14.104
- [sniffs]

51:14.187 --> 51:17.396
I was so terrified
I might never see you again.

51:17.479 --> 51:20.813
- Why?
- Because of... last night.

51:20.896 --> 51:24.521
Because I couldn't give you
what you wanted.

51:24.605 --> 51:26.855
[sniffs]

51:26.937 --> 51:29.896
[tender music]

51:29.979 --> 51:33.896
♪ ♪

51:33.979 --> 51:37.104
- These things take time.

51:37.187 --> 51:38.855
- [sniffs]

51:38.937 --> 51:45.979
♪ ♪

52:11.521 --> 52:15.771
- Ma! Ma!

52:15.855 --> 52:17.313
- What, is summat up?

52:17.396 --> 52:18.896
- Miss Lister wants to see him

52:18.979 --> 52:21.438
up at the hall.

52:21.521 --> 52:24.896
I'm going to have
to let him loose.

52:24.979 --> 52:26.354
I was wondering if you
should walk the little ones

52:26.438 --> 52:27.646
into Halifax for a while,

52:27.730 --> 52:28.896
and then, if he kicks off
and lashes out,

52:28.979 --> 52:30.062
they'll be out of the way.

52:30.146 --> 52:31.062
- What about you?

52:31.146 --> 52:32.855
- I can run faster than him,

52:32.937 --> 52:35.937
if he starts anything.

52:36.021 --> 52:40.271
- Alf, go find Amy.
We're going into Halifax.

52:40.354 --> 52:43.563
And you, just be careful,
and run.

52:43.646 --> 52:45.438
If you have to, just run.

52:45.521 --> 52:48.479
[dramatic music]

52:48.563 --> 52:55.563
♪ ♪

53:04.563 --> 53:07.354
- Miss Lister wants to see you

53:07.438 --> 53:08.813
up at the hall,

53:08.896 --> 53:10.313
and God knows you have
some talking to do,

53:10.396 --> 53:12.813
'cause she isn't happy
with you,

53:12.896 --> 53:14.187
so I don't know.

53:14.271 --> 53:15.730
I don't know.

53:15.813 --> 53:17.229
Oh, I don't know.

53:19.771 --> 53:21.187
The thing is,
even if I let you loose

53:21.271 --> 53:22.313
and you went up there,

53:22.396 --> 53:24.979
chances are,
she'd just kick us off anyway,

53:25.062 --> 53:27.271
way she were talking,

53:27.354 --> 53:28.937
so I don't know.

53:30.354 --> 53:32.104
But you better say
the right thing.

53:32.187 --> 53:34.021
You should get yourself
cleaned up

53:34.104 --> 53:35.937
and say the right thing
to her.

53:36.021 --> 53:39.021
[suspenseful music]

53:39.104 --> 53:46.104
♪ ♪

53:50.771 --> 53:52.646
- I'll kill you!
I'll kill you!

53:52.730 --> 53:55.605
[yells]

53:55.688 --> 53:57.730
[yells, grunts]

53:57.813 --> 53:59.146
Get me off this fucking chair!

53:59.229 --> 54:01.605
Get me out
of this fucking chair!

54:01.688 --> 54:04.271
Untie me!
Get me out of this chair!

54:04.354 --> 54:06.563
Get me off this fucking chair!

54:06.646 --> 54:07.771
Untie me!

54:07.855 --> 54:08.937
[yells]

54:09.021 --> 54:10.396
I'm gonna rip your innards
through your asshole,

54:10.479 --> 54:12.646
you little sod!
Untie me!

54:12.730 --> 54:14.313
I'll kill you!

54:14.396 --> 54:17.855
[Sam continues yelling]

54:17.937 --> 54:19.229
- You know
one of the only things

54:19.313 --> 54:20.730
I ever learned from you, eh?

54:20.813 --> 54:23.354
- Get me off
this fucking chair!

54:23.438 --> 54:24.479
- Eh?

54:25.813 --> 54:27.021
You ignorant bastard!

54:28.479 --> 54:31.146
When I were little,

54:31.229 --> 54:34.313
"The thing about a hungry pig,"
you said,

54:34.396 --> 54:38.271
"is that it'll eat anything
and everything.

54:38.354 --> 54:40.563
Absolutely..."

54:40.646 --> 54:42.062
[dramatic music]

54:42.146 --> 54:44.688
- [yells]
- "Anything."

54:47.479 --> 54:49.979
[pigs squealing]

54:57.855 --> 55:00.771
[gentle music]

55:00.855 --> 55:07.896
♪ ♪

55:15.937 --> 55:18.937
[music swells]

55:19.021 --> 55:26.062
♪ ♪

55:41.605 --> 55:43.563
- Good morning!

55:43.646 --> 55:47.146
- Morning, ma'am.

55:47.229 --> 55:48.646
- I'm sorry to be--

55:48.730 --> 55:51.896
just, I noticed
the blinds were down,

55:51.979 --> 55:54.521
and I wondered
is Miss Walker ill?

55:54.605 --> 55:56.979
- No, ma'am,
she's with Miss Lister.

55:57.062 --> 55:59.396
- [pants]

55:59.479 --> 56:02.396
[moans]

56:02.479 --> 56:04.354
♪ ♪

56:04.438 --> 56:06.855
I love you.

56:06.937 --> 56:09.855
♪ ♪

56:09.937 --> 56:11.730
- Don't knock.

56:11.813 --> 56:13.062
- Sorry, ma'am?

56:13.146 --> 56:15.146
♪ ♪

56:15.229 --> 56:18.187
[both moaning, panting]

56:18.271 --> 56:21.062
[door opens]

56:21.146 --> 56:23.146
- What?

56:27.479 --> 56:29.313
What are you doing?

56:30.438 --> 56:32.062
- Nothing.

56:32.146 --> 56:34.563
- You were--you were--

56:34.646 --> 56:35.605
- I'm not feeling well.

56:35.688 --> 56:37.187
Miss Lister's been looking
after me.

56:37.271 --> 56:39.104
- Oh, I see.

56:39.187 --> 56:42.396
Is that what you call it?

56:42.479 --> 56:43.563
- Sorry?

56:43.646 --> 56:44.730
- For years,

56:44.813 --> 56:45.979
I have defended you

56:46.062 --> 56:47.271
against comments.

56:47.354 --> 56:50.438
- Eliza--
- Don't you "Eliza" me!

56:50.521 --> 56:52.396
Your aunt has been
in a host of miseries

56:52.479 --> 56:55.688
with you staying out late,
and this--

56:55.771 --> 56:58.021
you--

56:58.104 --> 57:00.771
you're playing with fire.

57:00.855 --> 57:03.813
Do you understand?
Both of you.

57:08.813 --> 57:10.937
Oh.

57:11.021 --> 57:12.438
[bird tweets]

57:20.146 --> 57:23.396
- [chuckling]

57:24.479 --> 57:27.521
[laughing]

57:32.229 --> 57:33.521
[knock at door]

57:33.605 --> 57:35.479
[door opens]

57:35.563 --> 57:37.354
- Is everything all right,

57:37.438 --> 57:38.605
Miss Walker?

57:38.688 --> 57:41.187
- Yes, thank you, James.

57:43.479 --> 57:49.896
[laughs]

57:51.438 --> 57:53.605
Should we go upstairs?

57:53.688 --> 57:56.605
[jaunty piano music]

57:56.688 --> 58:03.771
♪ ♪

58:42.730 --> 58:43.937
[moans]

58:44.021 --> 58:51.104
♪ ♪

58:53.730 --> 58:56.313
[frantic squealing]

58:56.396 --> 59:03.438
♪ ♪

59:42.688 --> 59:44.937
- ♪ Behind her back,
she's Gentleman Jack ♪

59:45.021 --> 59:47.062
♪ A Yorkshire lady
of renown ♪

59:47.146 --> 59:49.313
♪ Ever so fine,
won't toe the line ♪

59:49.396 --> 59:51.396
♪ Speak her name
and gentlemen frown ♪

59:51.479 --> 59:53.354
♪ At Shibden Hall,
she had them all ♪

59:53.438 --> 59:55.771
♪ The fairer sex
fell under her spell ♪

59:55.855 --> 59:58.146
♪ Dapper and bright,
she held them tight ♪

59:58.229 --> 1:00:00.229
♪ Handsome Anne
seduced them well ♪

1:00:00.313 --> 1:00:02.271
♪ Gentleman Jack,
oh, Gentleman Jack ♪

1:00:02.354 --> 1:00:04.396
♪ Watch your back,
you're under attack ♪

1:00:04.479 --> 1:00:06.688
♪ Their husbands are coming,
you'd better start running ♪

1:00:06.771 --> 1:00:09.062
♪ For nobody likes
a Jack-the-lass ♪

1:00:09.146 --> 1:00:10.937
♪ Jack-the-lass,
Jack-the-lass ♪

1:00:11.021 --> 1:00:13.104
♪ No one likes
a Jack-the-lass ♪

1:00:13.187 --> 1:00:15.438
♪ The code is cracked,
your bags are packed ♪

1:00:15.521 --> 1:00:18.021
♪ The knives are out
for Gentleman Jack ♪

1:00:19.271 --> 1:00:21.354
[bright tone]

1:00:24.354 --> 1:00:25.979
WOMAN:
It appears you have my niece

1:00:26.062 --> 1:00:28.104
quite under your spell,
Miss Lister.

1:00:28.646 --> 1:00:30.688
I'd rather think
she has me under hers.

1:00:32.021 --> 1:00:34.271
I've had a tenant...
disappeared.

1:00:34.521 --> 1:00:36.730
How's things with Tom?
Any sign of him?

1:00:37.979 --> 1:00:40.354
ANNE LISTER: The Rawsons.
They've been stealing my coal.

1:00:40.605 --> 1:00:42.354
I told you,
it's a nasty business.

1:00:42.771 --> 1:00:45.146
ANN WALKER: I've had a letter
from Mr. Ainsworth.

1:00:45.354 --> 1:00:46.646
Do you think I should marry him?

1:00:47.187 --> 1:00:49.271
If you take him,
you'd have to give me up.

1:00:49.688 --> 1:00:51.813
If I did,
it would be out of duty.

1:00:52.187 --> 1:00:53.813
LISTER: Do you really think
that I'm someone to have

1:00:53.896 --> 1:00:56.313
my future happiness
decided by fate?

1:00:56.896 --> 1:00:58.730
You're going to have
to make a decision.
